<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="First_World_War">First World War</span></h2>
<p>The 4th Canadian Division was formed in the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">Britain</a> in April 1916 from several existing units and others scheduled to arrive shortly thereafter. Under the command of <a href="/wiki/Major-General" title="Major-General" class="mw-redirect">Major-General</a> <a href="/wiki/David_Watson_(general)" title="David Watson (general)">David Watson</a>, the Division embarked for France in August of that year where they served both in France and in <a href="/wiki/Flanders" title="Flanders">Flanders</a> until <a href="/wiki/Armistice_Day" title="Armistice Day">Armistice Day</a>. The 4th Canadian Division was a part of the <a href="/wiki/Canadian_Corps" title="Canadian Corps">Canadian Corps</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Vimy_Ridge" title="Battle of Vimy Ridge">Battle of Vimy Ridge</a>, which attacked and defeated the Germans, driving them from the ridge. As a result the Canadians became known as masters of offensive warfare and an elite fighting force.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Vimy_Ridge" title="Battle of Vimy Ridge">Battle of Vimy Ridge</a>, the 4th Canadian Division was given the job of capturing <a href="/w/index.php?title=Hill_145&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Hill 145 (page does not exist)">Hill 145</a>, the highest and most important feature of <a href="/wiki/Vimy_Ridge" title="Vimy Ridge" class="mw-redirect">Vimy Ridge</a>. However, when they attempted to capture the hill, they were hampered by fire from the "Pimple", which was the other prominent height at Vimy Ridge. To capture Hill 145, forces which were supposed to attack the Pimple were redeployed and captured Hill 145.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Infantry_Units">Infantry Units</span></h3>
<p><b>10th Canadian Brigade:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/w/index.php?title=44th_Battalion,_CEF&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="44th Battalion, CEF (page does not exist)">44th (Manitoba) Battalion Canadian Infantry</a>. April 1916 - 11 November 1918. (Re-designated New Brunswick in August 1918);</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/46th_Battalion,_CEF" title="46th Battalion, CEF" class="mw-redirect">46th (South Saskatchewan) Battalion Canadian Infantry</a>. April 1916 - 11 November 1918;</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Royal_Westminster_Regiment" title="Royal Westminster Regiment">47th (British Columbia) Battalion Canadian Infantry</a>. April 1916 - 11 November 1918. (Re-designated West Ontario in February 1918);</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/50th_Battalion,_CEF" title="50th Battalion, CEF" class="mw-redirect">50th (Calgary) Battalion Canadian Infantry</a>. April 1916 - 11 November 1918.</li>
</ul>
