<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="4th_Canadian_.28Armoured.29_Division">4th Canadian (Armoured) Division</span></h2>
<p>The <b>4th Canadian (Armoured) Division</b> was created by the conversion of the 4th Canadian Infantry Division at the beginning of 1942 in Canada. The division proceeded overseas in 1942, with its two main <a href="/wiki/Convoy" title="Convoy">convoys</a> reaching the United Kingdom in August and October.</p>
<p>The division spent almost two years training in the UK before crossing to <a href="/wiki/Normandy" title="Normandy">Normandy</a> in July 1944. In UK, it did participate in war games together with the <a href="/wiki/1st_Armoured_Division_(Poland)" title="1st Armoured Division (Poland)">1st Armoured Division (Poland)</a>, and in France, <a href="/wiki/Low_Countries" title="Low Countries">Low Countries</a>, and Germany, both divisions followed very close paths. It participated in the battle of the Falaise pocket, the advance from Normandy and spent almost two months engaged at the <a href="/wiki/Breskens_pocket" title="Breskens pocket" class="mw-redirect">Breskens pocket</a>. It wintered in the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">Netherlands</a> and took part in the final advance across northern Germany. The division is to be reactivated with the renaming of <a href="/wiki/Land_Force_Central_Area" title="Land Force Central Area">Land Force Central Area</a></p>
